00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:03,360
And I think we have the support of our business 
partners because so many great insights have come  

188
00:17:03,360 --> 00:17:09,280
from these deep dives and it really has been 
some of the work that drives future roadmaps.  

189
00:17:09,280 --> 00:17:15,560
So they're always really great at allowing us to 
have this time and actually encourage us often  

190
00:17:15,560 --> 00:17:21,560
to have this time for some self-directed 
work, to go find the next big opportunity.

191
00:17:23,280 --> 00:17:25,680
If there's no answer that comes to mind,  

192
00:17:25,680 --> 00:17:30,400
that's totally cool. But is there an example 
of one of these insights that someone on the  

193
00:17:30,400 --> 00:17:35,120
data team came up with that led to something 
big for DoorDash that you're able to share?

194
00:17:35,120 --> 00:17:41,720
So one interesting example was from a hackathon we 
did a couple of years ago where we were looking at  

195
00:17:41,720 --> 00:17:49,360
referral as a channel for consumer acquisition. 
And when you compare that channel to others,  

196
00:17:49,360 --> 00:17:56,320
it was below average in terms of the engagement 
you'd see from consumers who came through that  

197
00:17:56,320 --> 00:18:03,880
channel and the payback period. And rather than 
just lowering spend on referrals and moving right  

198
00:18:03,880 --> 00:18:10,440
along, we really wanted to understand what 
was happening. And so during the hackathon,  

199
00:18:10,440 --> 00:18:17,480
we did a deep dive into referral. We actually 
tried referring each other. We tried committing  

200
00:18:17,480 --> 00:18:22,440
referral fraud, creating new accounts to 
get around rules. And we uncovered a lot  

201
00:18:22,440 --> 00:18:28,760
of fraudulent behavior through this deep dive. We 
ordered so many cupcakes to the office. I remember  

202
00:18:29,600 --> 00:18:34,560
using referral credits because you had to place 
an order to be able to get the referral bonus.  

203
00:18:34,560 --> 00:18:39,400
So we would create the account, place the 
orders, and we just kept ordering cupcakes. 

204
00:18:39,400 --> 00:18:46,360
And what we noticed was that referral as 
a channel was a bit misleading when you  

205
00:18:46,360 --> 00:18:52,160
would look at the average in terms of payback 
and that it was really a bimodal distribution  

206
00:18:52,160 --> 00:18:58,720
and you had one group of really great consumers 
who were referring other really great consumers,  

207
00:18:59,240 --> 00:19:05,520
and the payback on those consumers was really 
strong. In fact, if that's all you saw,  

208
00:19:05,520 --> 00:19:12,320
you would spend a lot more on that channel.
And then what was happening was you had this  

209
00:19:12,320 --> 00:19:19,160
other group of consumers that were not as good 
people who were posting referral codes online  

210
00:19:19,160 --> 00:19:26,560
and getting people who were just in it to get 
free discounts and credits. And we had at that  

211
00:19:26,560 --> 00:19:32,840
point in time, pretty lax fraud rules. And we 
didn't have caps on these things. All of which  

212
00:19:32,840 --> 00:19:41,400
came about from this deep dive where we found 
that this group of consumers was really a drag  

213
00:19:41,400 --> 00:19:48,080
on the efficiency of this marketing channel. And 
so I think that's an example of a few things that  

214
00:19:48,080 --> 00:19:55,440
we like to do at DoorDash. One being these deep 
dives and taking the time to really understand  

215
00:19:55,440 --> 00:20:00,320
the problem and then ultimately make a bunch 
of recommendations for what we should do,  

216
00:20:00,320 --> 00:20:06,840
including better fraud checks, caps on referrals, 
et cetera, et cetera. But also how the average  

217
00:20:06,840 --> 00:20:14,360
can be incredibly misleading. And so looking at 
distributions and trying to break down what you're  

218
00:20:14,360 --> 00:20:21,040
seeing to find ways that you can optimize 
in ways that you can gain in efficiencies.

219
00:20:21,040 --> 00:20:27,240
That's an awesome story, great memory to come up 
with that one. So this is a really good example  

220
00:20:27,240 --> 00:20:32,480
of a way to carve out time for the data team to 
think long-term, think look for opportunities,  

221
00:20:32,480 --> 00:20:38,920
find big ideas. So the hackathon is one idea. 
Imagine many data people are struggling often  

222
00:20:38,920 --> 00:20:42,640
to push back on asks that are just like, "h, we 
need to know. We just need this one thing. Here's  

223
00:20:42,640 --> 00:20:49,440
a question, just answer this one question part." 
Do you have any advice to data to get better at  

224
00:20:49,440 --> 00:20:53,520
pushing back? Sounds like a bit of cultural like, 
"We have time, we need to work on these bigger  

225
00:20:53,520 --> 00:20:58,600
things." But just any advice for data leaders or 
data ICs to find time for these sorts of things?

226
00:20:59,920 --> 00:21:07,280
Yeah, saying no to someone is never fun. I 
think as a self-proclaimed people-pleaser,  

227
00:21:07,280 --> 00:21:10,640
you don't want to say no, especially when it's 
something you can do and you know that you can  

228
00:21:10,640 --> 00:21:15,880
very easily with maybe an hour's work, make 
someone happy. I think it's really important  

229
00:21:16,560 --> 00:21:23,280
to establish a culture and for leadership 
to really establish the rules of working  

230
00:21:23,280 --> 00:21:28,800
and that operating model so that some of the 
junior folks aren't forced to always have to  

231
00:21:28,800 --> 00:21:34,960
say no. And I think one of the ways we do that 
is through our goaling. So because our goals  

232
00:21:34,960 --> 00:21:39,440
are the same as our business partners, 
we're able to pretty easily say, "Hey,  

233
00:21:39,440 --> 00:21:42,760
we've got a limited amount of time. These are 
our goals. What are the most important things  

234
00:21:42,760 --> 00:21:49,200
that we are going to work on this week or this 
month in order for both of us to hit our goals?" 

235
00:21:49,200 --> 00:21:56,320
And so when something comes up to be able to say, 
"Hey, this data poll that you want me to do, is  

236
00:21:56,320 --> 00:22:03,560
this more important than these other three things 
that I was going to be working on? Yes or no?" And  

237
00:22:03,560 --> 00:22:10,200
I think sometimes people don't necessarily realize 
the trade-offs, and when you make them apparent  

238
00:22:10,200 --> 00:22:15,320
and you put them front and center, they realize 
that, "Oh, actually, you know what? That asset's  

239
00:22:15,320 --> 00:22:19,720
not important. That can wait." So I think that 
that's definitely something I would recommend,  

240
00:22:19,720 --> 00:22:24,000
which is always share the trade-offs. Don't 
suffer in silence with, "How am I going to do  

241
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:28,760
all four of these things?" Bring it up and say, 
"Hey, this is what I was planning to do. If you  

242
00:22:28,760 --> 00:22:34,600
want me to do this extra new thing, then one 
of these other things is going to have to drop. 

243
00:22:35,920 --> 00:22:40,240
I personally don't think that your ask is more 
important than these three things, but maybe  

244
00:22:40,240 --> 00:22:44,520
there's new information, maybe there's context I 
don't have, so let's talk about it." Rather than  

245
00:22:44,520 --> 00:22:49,200
just being like, "No, I won't do that." That's 
not a great approach either. I think having the  

246
00:22:49,200 --> 00:22:54,200
conversation and constantly reevaluating your 
prioritization to make sure you're working  

247
00:22:54,200 --> 00:22:58,680
on the most important things or your team is 
working on the most important things is really  

248
00:22:58,680 --> 00:23:04,400
good hygiene to have with your business partner. 
So some teams do that through a weekly standup  

249
00:23:04,400 --> 00:23:08,840
like, "Here's what we're going to do this week. 
Do we like this prioritization? Do we not?" Some  

250
00:23:08,840 --> 00:23:14,040
folks do it less formally than that. I think 
you got to figure out what works for you. But  

251
00:23:14,040 --> 00:23:20,640
to the earlier point, it's a conversation with 
your engineering partner, your product partner,  

252
00:23:20,640 --> 00:23:25,080
your ops partner, you're all on the same team, 
you're all trying to achieve the same goals and  

253
00:23:25,080 --> 00:23:32,000
you're all incentivized to have your analytics 
team working on the most impactful things.

254
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:37,880
This advice is great for any role basically. 
And if I were to summarize it to a couple words,  

255
00:23:37,880 --> 00:23:40,880
it's just prioritize and communicate what your  

256
00:23:40,880 --> 00:23:45,800
priorities are and then align on the 
trade-offs of shifting your priorities.

257
00:23:45,800 --> 00:23:48,280
Every once in a while you 
just throw one over and say,  

258
00:23:48,280 --> 00:23:54,080
"You know what? This is quick. I'll do it." At 
least I do. I think sometimes just knock it out,  

259
00:23:54,080 --> 00:23:58,640
build some goodwill. I think that that's also 
important. But usually it's not something  

260
00:23:58,640 --> 00:24:05,120
you can do in five minutes and in that case 
it's that ruthless prioritization for sure.

261
00:24:05,120 --> 00:24:08,600
And then there's also the side that you 
talked about of just show that you can  

262
00:24:08,600 --> 00:24:12,360
provide value doing these things that are 
longer term, like prove your worth. "Hey,  

263
00:24:12,360 --> 00:24:14,680
look at all these opportunities 
I found for our team over time,  

264
00:24:14,680 --> 00:24:19,100
I should keep spending time on these 
other areas," versus the on fire stuff.

265
00:24:19,100 --> 00:24:19,920
Exactly.

266
00:24:19,920 --> 00:24:23,080
When you're hiring people for your team,  

267
00:24:23,080 --> 00:24:27,240
I'm curious what you look for and you 
think is incredibly important that maybe  

268
00:24:27,240 --> 00:24:31,760
other people aren't prioritizing as much. 
What do you focus on when you're hiring?

269
00:24:31,760 --> 00:24:38,520
Yeah. So everybody needs to have a certain set of 
technical skills. I think that's a non-starter. We  

270
00:24:38,520 --> 00:24:44,400
have a technical bar, we do a technical screen. 
So I think that's table stakes. There's some  

271
00:24:44,400 --> 00:24:49,600
really unique characteristics that I've noticed 
when I look at some of the top talent that I've  

272
00:24:49,600 --> 00:24:55,040
had on the team or have on the team. I think 
the first thing is just curiosity. You can't  

273
00:24:55,040 --> 00:25:00,280
teach curiosity, or at least I haven't found 
a way to do it. If somebody else knows how,  

274
00:25:00,280 --> 00:25:05,520
please let me know. Somebody who is just 
self-motivated to pull on the threads when they  

275
00:25:05,520 --> 00:25:11,520
find them. So they don't just answer a question. 
They're like, "Hmm, this thing seems a little odd.  

276
00:25:11,520 --> 00:25:18,560
I'm going to dig in and look. Even though I could 
say I'm done, I answered the question, I did the  

277
00:25:18,560 --> 00:25:24,760
thing I was going to do." The person that has 
that curiosity, something seems off, something  

278
00:25:24,760 --> 00:25:32,720
doesn't really make sense and goes and proactively 
looks into what that is. That is just so valuable.  

279
00:25:32,720 --> 00:25:39,080
So I really look for that curiosity and that 
self-motivation to do it without being told.

280
00:25:39,080 --> 00:25:40,480
How do you test for that? How do you do that in  

281
00:25:40,480 --> 00:25:43,440
an interview and get a sense 
of if they're good at that?

282
00:25:43,440 --> 00:25:48,840
One way you can do it through the questions 
you ask is have something that is not quite  

283
00:25:48,840 --> 00:25:54,680
right within the case that you're presenting 
and see if people notice first and foremost.  

284
00:25:54,680 --> 00:26:00,560
And even if they don't, if you point it out 
like, "Where do they go with that?" I think  

285
00:26:00,560 --> 00:26:08,840
that that's something that you can test for. 
I think you can also ask for examples that for  

286
00:26:08,840 --> 00:26:14,760
these folks typically will highlight this, 
they'll talk about, "I noticed this thing,  

287
00:26:14,760 --> 00:26:23,600
and so we decided to investigate." So I think 
that there are ways that you can get that signal  

288
00:26:23,600 --> 00:26:30,480
through the interview process, but it's really 
hard. I think testing for hard skills is a lot  

289
00:26:30,480 --> 00:26:35,400
easier than testing for soft skills. And 
I think in some of the questions we ask,  

290
00:26:35,400 --> 00:26:41,040
we'll ask a question with the idea that we're 
assessing something separate than what the  

291
00:26:41,040 --> 00:26:47,040
question is necessarily asking. And I think that 
this is one example of where that really works.

292
00:26:47,040 --> 00:26:49,360
You said that you give them a case. 
What does that look like? What is  

293
00:26:49,360 --> 00:26:52,440
the actual approach to how you do this interview?

294
00:26:52,440 --> 00:27:00,960
Our interview process has in the early stages a 
coding exercise. So we do our technical screen  

295
00:27:00,960 --> 00:27:07,240
and a shortened version of a business case. 
So real world problem solving. Typically,  

296
00:27:07,240 --> 00:27:15,320
it's something actually from DoorDash history, 
like a real problem that we had to see how people  

297
00:27:15,320 --> 00:27:21,360
can problem solve on the fly. I think that that's 
an important skill to be able to have, which is,  

298
00:27:21,360 --> 00:27:26,120
how do you take a problem, break it down, 
talk through it. A little bit like some of  

299
00:27:26,120 --> 00:27:33,040
those consulting cases that you hear about, 
but something that's really rooted in real  

300
00:27:33,040 --> 00:27:40,440
problems. And I think you can learn a lot from 
those types of cases where, yes, you get to see  

301
00:27:40,440 --> 00:27:47,720
how people handle ambiguity and structured problem 
solving, but ultimately most people get something  

302
00:27:47,720 --> 00:27:53,360
wrong. They make an assumption that's wrong 
because well, I would hope that the interviewer  

303
00:27:53,360 --> 00:27:59,240
knows the business better than the interviewee.
And seeing how people react to being told they're  

304
00:27:59,240 --> 00:28:07,040
wrong is a really important signal in my opinion. 
Seeing how people respond, how they're able to  

305
00:28:07,040 --> 00:28:13,240
take new information and pivot, how they're able 
to make a decision. So that's another thing that  

306
00:28:13,240 --> 00:28:20,840
I like to see in cases where, hey, you may not 
know the real right decision. You might say, "Hey,  

307
00:28:22,200 --> 00:28:25,920
I could see it going one way, I could see it going 
the other way." But I always push people to say,  

308
00:28:25,920 --> 00:28:30,360
"If you had to make a call right now, what 
would it be?" So are people able to have a  

309
00:28:30,360 --> 00:28:37,440
point of view without full information because 
that's life. Sometimes you have to just pick  

310
00:28:37,440 --> 00:28:42,080
a direction and make a decision even though 
you don't have perfect information. So I like  

311
00:28:42,080 --> 00:28:49,320
to see some of these softer skills and how 
they manifest throughout a case interview,  

312
00:28:49,320 --> 00:28:57,320
even if it's not specifically what I'm asking with 
the literal problem we're solving in the case.

313
00:28:57,320 --> 00:29:01,840
Along these lines, but in a different direction. 
You don't actually have a deep data science  

314
00:29:01,840 --> 00:29:06,520
data background before you got into this 
stuff. I know you had some art background,  

315
00:29:07,480 --> 00:29:12,680
you had an art portfolio back in school, and 
I think a lot of people wouldn't imagine that  

316
00:29:12,680 --> 00:29:19,080
for someone being head of analytics for a company 
like DoorDash. I don't exactly know the question,  

317
00:29:19,080 --> 00:29:24,600
but I guess is there anything there that you think 
would be interesting for people to know or hear?

318
00:29:24,600 --> 00:29:29,520
Yeah, it's funny. I joke that I have a job 
I'd never be hired for because I don't have a  

319
00:29:29,520 --> 00:29:34,840
traditional data science background. And I know 
that Elizabeth Stone on her podcast with you  

320
00:29:34,840 --> 00:29:40,000
talked a lot about her non-traditional background 
for a CTO. So hey, maybe there's something to it.  

321
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:48,800
But I became a data scientist out of necessity. I 
completely self-taught in terms of SQL and Python  

322
00:29:48,800 --> 00:29:57,720
and I did it because there was a need at DoorDash 
for someone to help figure out what the right  

323
00:29:57,720 --> 00:30:06,200
goals were, how we set those goals, how we were 
performing different markets early in the DoorDash  

324
00:30:06,200 --> 00:30:18,160
story, so 10 years ago at this point. And I think 
I just gravitated towards that type of work and  

325
00:30:18,160 --> 00:30:23,920
Tony recognized that superpower in me even though 
I don't have that formal training. So yeah,  

326
00:30:23,920 --> 00:30:31,320
I'm a bit of an artist for fun, but I guess 
a data scientist in practice or for career. 

327
00:30:31,320 --> 00:30:39,240
But I think that that non-traditional background 
has been a great thing because I'm able to hire  

328
00:30:39,240 --> 00:30:47,280
people who have the technical skills that I don't 
have, the folks with PhDs in statistics and the  

329
00:30:47,280 --> 00:30:53,440
data scientists, machine learning and otherwise. 
I am able to hire those folks and yet keep them  

330
00:30:53,440 --> 00:31:00,680
really focused on driving business impact because 
my background was on the finance side, and so  

331
00:31:00,680 --> 00:31:07,480
I've always been a pragmatist. And for me, the 
purpose of our team is to drive business impact.  

332
00:31:07,480 --> 00:31:14,360
And so the mix between the technical skills of the 
smarter people that I've hired, the smarter than  

333
00:31:14,360 --> 00:31:21,400
myself, and my grounding in driving business 
impact has been a really great partnership.

334
00:31:21,400 --> 00:31:25,840
That's quite an inspiring story for 
someone that is just starting out and  

335
00:31:25,840 --> 00:31:30,560
doesn't necessarily have a lot of experience 
in data, but also just generally. I think  

336
00:31:30,560 --> 00:31:34,680
this is a really cool example. You could 
be successful in a field that you don't  

337
00:31:34,680 --> 00:31:41,560
have a ton of background in. I'm curious 
what you think it was in you that allowed  

338
00:31:41,560 --> 00:31:46,480
you to succeed in this and get to where you 
are today. What do you think you did right or  

339
00:31:46,480 --> 00:31:52,800
what is some habits or ways of thinking 
that you think helped you achieve that?

340
00:31:52,800 --> 00:31:59,680
First off, I have imposter syndrome like everybody 
else. So it's not like I have this crazy sense of  

341
00:31:59,680 --> 00:32:06,480
confidence of like, "Oh, I can do anything." 
I definitely have the same doubts that others  

342
00:32:06,480 --> 00:32:12,080
have. I think part of it was probably not even 
realizing what I was doing. When you're at a  

343
00:32:12,080 --> 00:32:16,600
startup and things are moving quickly and you see 
a problem, and I've always liked solving problems,  

344
00:32:16,600 --> 00:32:20,520
so I was like, "All right, how do I solve this 
problem?" It was like, "Oh, well, I need access  

345
00:32:20,520 --> 00:32:25,000
to the data. I don't have access to the data. All 
right, I'll ask an engineer to get me the data.  

346
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:31,160
Well, this isn't going to scale. I can't always 
bother an engineer, so how do I figure out how to  

347
00:32:31,160 --> 00:32:38,280
get the data myself? Well, let's learn Python." So 
I think it happened organically and I don't think  

348
00:32:38,280 --> 00:32:45,080
I realized at the time what I was even doing.
And then I think if you think about things from  

349
00:32:45,080 --> 00:32:50,560
first principles about what you need right now 
in front of you to unblock yourself or solve a  

350
00:32:50,560 --> 00:32:57,120
problem, and you just focus on that instead of 
thinking about a global org that you're trying  

351
00:32:57,120 --> 00:33:03,400
to build. I think that that helps. So for me, it 
was always about solving the problem in front of  

352
00:33:03,400 --> 00:33:09,160
me the best way I could. And if that meant I 
needed to hire an engineer to report into me  

353
00:33:09,160 --> 00:33:14,440
through the finance org, then that was what we 
were going to do and nobody was going to tell  

354
00:33:14,440 --> 00:33:23,480
me I couldn't do it. So I think it's a belief 
in yourself, and ultimately it's just my desire  

355
00:33:23,480 --> 00:33:30,720
to solve problems and figure out what has to get 
done is, I think, ultimately how it came about.

356
00:33:30,720 --> 00:33:34,040
I love that so much. There's so many 
elements there that I think a lot of  

357
00:33:34,040 --> 00:33:37,000
people can learn from. I feel like there's 
also this underlying current of you're  

358
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:41,840
just motivated for this to work. You wanted 
DoorDash to succeed, and you're just like,  

359
00:33:41,840 --> 00:33:45,440
"I will do what I need to do to make this happen. 
I need to solve these problems. I'm not going to  

360
00:33:45,440 --> 00:33:48,920
overthink. Do I have the skills necessarily 
to do these things [inaudible 00:33:48]?"

361
00:33:48,920 --> 00:33:53,120
Yeah, I think I'm competitive. I think 
that's a trait that you find in a lot of  

362
00:33:53,120 --> 00:33:59,280
early DoorDash folks and current DoorDash 
folks, to be honest, just wanting to win  

363
00:33:59,280 --> 00:34:04,720
and being willing to do whatever you 
need to win. So roll up your sleeves,  

364
00:34:04,720 --> 00:34:10,960
do something that's not your job. I think back to 
early days of taking out the garbage on Saturday  

365
00:34:10,960 --> 00:34:18,680
nights because it needed to get done. I think 
that that was something that is ingrained in  

366
00:34:18,680 --> 00:34:27,800
our culture from Tony Xu, from our founder and 
CEO, and I think that really resonated with me,  

367
00:34:27,800 --> 00:34:34,720
and I feel like I've always operated that way 
as well. And I think that that helped me in  

368
00:34:34,720 --> 00:34:40,040
my career to be able to do what I've done 
without really thinking about it too much.

369
00:34:40,040 --> 00:34:44,240
Are there any other memories or stories of 
