00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:49,200
I've learned a lot of things about metrics, mostly 
from bad metrics. I actually think you learn a lot  

473
00:44:49,200 --> 00:44:57,240
from picking the wrong metric. Ultimately, you 
want to find a short-term metric you can measure  

474
00:44:57,240 --> 00:45:02,800
that drives a long-term output. So people always 
talk about, "Oh, we want to drive an improvement  

475
00:45:02,800 --> 00:45:11,160
in retention." Retention is a terrible thing to 
goal on because it's almost impossible to drive  

476
00:45:11,160 --> 00:45:16,440
in a meaningful way in the short term, and yet 
you want to be able to experiment and iterate  

477
00:45:16,440 --> 00:45:22,040
quickly. So what are the things that drive 
retention? What are the inputs? So I think  

478
00:45:22,040 --> 00:45:26,280
it's really important to find the right inputs, 
and then through experimentation test whether  

479
00:45:26,280 --> 00:45:32,240
or not those short-term inputs are driving the 
long-term output that you're looking for. I think  

480
00:45:32,240 --> 00:45:37,280
that's one thing. I think keeping things simple 
is another thing I've learned over the years,  

481
00:45:37,280 --> 00:45:43,960
maybe it's data scientists, but they tend to 
love these composite metrics with a coefficient. 

482
00:45:43,960 --> 00:45:51,440
"We're going to wait this input at X and this 
input at X+2." And then you end up with a  

483
00:45:51,440 --> 00:45:58,520
metric that nobody really understands that doesn't 
actually mean anything. And you're like, "I don't  

484
00:45:58,520 --> 00:46:07,080
