00:52:50,560 --> 00:52:56,440
So once we get success with that 95, then 
let's talk about figuring out the other 5%.

550
00:52:57,360 --> 00:53:00,720
It's so funny because this is exactly 
what we went through at Airbnb, we had,  

551
00:53:00,720 --> 00:53:04,360
we call that a healthy host. I led the 
host quality team for a while and we came  

552
00:53:04,360 --> 00:53:09,680
up with this healthy host metric that was six 
factors of a host, like the cancellation rate,  

553
00:53:09,680 --> 00:53:13,760
the review rate, their response rate and 
things like that. And then we're just like,  

554
00:53:13,760 --> 00:53:18,200
"Cool, let's move this, let make more hosts 
healthy." And then you end up like, "Okay,  

555
00:53:18,200 --> 00:53:22,160
which one do we focus on?," And, "Oh, what 
about all these others?" And we ended up  

556
00:53:22,160 --> 00:53:26,640
basically focusing on one at a time. And so let's 
just make that the goal for now and then rotate  

557
00:53:26,640 --> 00:53:29,400
through the different biggest [inaudible 00:53:28] 
opportunities to move. [inaudible 00:53:30].

558
00:53:29,400 --> 00:53:34,880
Exactly. I think in hindsight for the example 
you give, which of those six things are actually  

559
00:53:34,880 --> 00:53:40,080
the most important? And if you're able to then 
quantify which one matters most, you work on that  

560
00:53:40,080 --> 00:53:45,960
one first and you materially move that one and 
then you work on the next one. You want to move  

561
00:53:45,960 --> 00:53:52,360
them all. But being able to prioritize and know 
what you're going to get for a 20% improvement in,  

562
00:53:52,360 --> 00:53:56,680
say, your cancellation rate, that's where 
analytics I think can add a lot of value.  

563
00:53:56,680 --> 00:54:03,120
Because yes, ultimately you'll get to all of 
them, but the way you do that and the time can  

564
00:54:03,120 --> 00:54:08,520
have a meaningful impact on your growth. If you 
can target the most problematic things first and  

565
00:54:08,520 --> 00:54:14,880
solve those, you get more bang for your buck 
and that compounds over time. And so doing the  

566
00:54:14,880 --> 00:54:21,240
things that matter first and most quickly 
is a competitive advantage in my opinion.

567
00:54:21,240 --> 00:54:26,080
The other thing we found along those same lines 
is rotating between different metrics is so not  

568
00:54:26,080 --> 00:54:29,560
efficient because you get good at, "We're going 
to move this metric." And your team's like,  

569
00:54:29,560 --> 00:54:33,800
"Cool, we totally understand this 
lever," like cancellation rate. We  

570
00:54:33,800 --> 00:54:36,840
become really smart at cancellation 
rate and then three months later,  

571
00:54:36,840 --> 00:54:41,640
you need to switch to response rate and they 
have to learn a whole new paradigm of how to  

572
00:54:41,640 --> 00:54:46,480
think about it. And it's just super inefficient. 
So we found basically, just keep a team on the  

573
00:54:46,480 --> 00:54:51,040
metric until there's no more opportunities and 
give another team one of these other metrics.

574
00:54:51,040 --> 00:54:52,160
Yeah.

575
00:54:52,160 --> 00:54:57,520
So many lessons. Okay. And the first thing you 
said on how to pick a good metric about this idea  

576
00:54:57,520 --> 00:55:02,480
of short-term metrics that have long-term 
impact. How did you phrase that again?

