00:55:05,640 --> 00:55:10,880
Awesome. And it's similar to the simple 
metric, and it all comes down to, again,  

579
00:55:10,880 --> 00:55:16,000
just like the metric should be something 
probably, you can move, you can understand,  

580
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:22,440
that's close enough to this ideal, perfect metric, 
but isn't necessarily the entire ideal. Okay,  

581
00:55:22,440 --> 00:55:24,800
awesome. Anything else along these 
lines of just picking metrics,  

582
00:55:24,800 --> 00:55:27,960
working with metrics that you've learned 
that would be worth [inaudible 00:55:28]?

583
00:55:27,960 --> 00:55:31,040
With metrics, we are often looking at the average,  

584
00:55:31,040 --> 00:55:34,800
and I think we talked about this a little bit 
earlier, but making sure that you're looking at  

585
00:55:34,800 --> 00:55:40,200
the edge cases and your fail states is also 
really important. And so we often will set  

586
00:55:40,200 --> 00:55:48,560
goals actually and create metrics around those 
edge cases. So like the disaster deliveries,  

587
00:55:48,560 --> 00:55:54,200
the ones that go terribly wrong. So we 
have this concept of Never Delivered,  

588
00:55:54,200 --> 00:55:59,520
which is orders that are never delivered. We're 
really great at naming things at DoorDash,  

589
00:55:59,520 --> 00:56:07,040
and they're very rare. And so if you were just 
looking at the average effect or the average  

590
00:56:07,040 --> 00:56:14,800
consumer experience, it would never come up. If 
you were just measuring quality based on average  

591
00:56:14,800 --> 00:56:20,760
values of delivery times and lateness [inaudible 
00:56:18], these wouldn't show up because they are  

592
00:56:20,760 --> 00:56:27,400
so rare, but they're terrible. They're terrible 
experiences for consumers. They lead to churn. 

593
00:56:27,400 --> 00:56:33,560
They're incredibly expensive because you're 
refunding an order or repurchasing food and having  

594
00:56:33,560 --> 00:56:39,720
to send another dasher to deliver that repurchased 
food. So they're very expensive, they're costly  

595
00:56:39,720 --> 00:56:45,440
from a consumer experience standpoint. And I think 
if you're not looking for these fail states, they  

596
00:56:45,440 --> 00:56:52,480
are often missed. So I think when you're picking 
metrics, yes, you want to improve engagement and  

597
00:56:52,480 --> 00:56:59,920
you want to improve conversion, and there's a lot 
of things that are averages overall that you want  

598
00:56:59,920 --> 00:57:05,280
to move, but it's so important to find these 
edge cases in these fail states and actually  

599
00:57:05,280 --> 00:57:11,640
set concrete goals around eliminating 
them because it can be really powerful.

600
00:57:11,640 --> 00:57:14,120
So the tip here is actually make that a goal like,  

601
00:57:14,120 --> 00:57:17,760
never deliver at some team, 
just keep cutting that down?

602
00:57:17,760 --> 00:57:24,400
Exactly. So we have part of our quality analytics 
team and we have product engineering and ops on  

603
00:57:24,400 --> 00:57:30,520
it as well. Their goal is to eradicate Never 
Delivered. And in order to do that, you have to  

604
00:57:30,520 --> 00:57:37,520
understand why they happen. Sometimes it's human 
error, sometimes it's fraud. And then figure out  

605
00:57:37,520 --> 00:57:45,320
ways that you can prevent them, that you can fix 
them while it's happening and ultimately just  

606
00:57:45,320 --> 00:57:49,560
get rid of them from the system. And you're 
never going to completely get rid of them,  

607
00:57:49,560 --> 00:58:00,400
but you can make a meaningful impact to make 
them even more rare than a fraction of a percent.

608
00:58:00,400 --> 00:58:04,320
Yeah. And I feel like people may be hearing 
this and like, "Of course, why would you not  

609
00:58:04,320 --> 00:58:09,920
focus on terrible work experiences?" But I think 
in most companies, they look at the big numbers,  

610
00:58:09,920 --> 00:58:14,440
they look at the averages as you said like, "Oh, 
it almost never happens. Why do we even spend any  

611
00:58:14,440 --> 00:58:18,480
time on this?" And your point is, you should 
actually spend time on these really terrible  

612
00:58:18,480 --> 00:58:22,440
experiences, even if it's a tiny portion 
of your business. I guess maybe share why  

613
00:58:22,440 --> 00:58:27,720
that's important. Is it just because that 
has trickle-down effects on the brand?

614
00:58:27,720 --> 00:58:31,680
Yeah, I think it's a couple of things. So just 
because something doesn't happen frequently  

615
00:58:31,680 --> 00:58:38,720
doesn't mean that it's not important. So 
the Never Delivered example is a great one  

616
00:58:38,720 --> 00:58:45,520
in that this is leading directly to churn 
and it's also costing a lot of money far  

617
00:58:45,520 --> 00:58:51,240
more than its frequency would suggest. And I 
think the fact of the matter is is when you  

618
00:58:51,240 --> 00:58:56,360
have things that cause churn, you're losing 
all of that consumer's subsequent orders,  

619
00:58:56,360 --> 00:59:02,560
and that is not necessarily observed. You're just 
seeing one bad experience, you're not seeing all  

620
00:59:02,560 --> 00:59:08,360
of the lost orders because they're lost. And 
so I think that sometimes this is an area where  

621
00:59:08,360 --> 00:59:16,560
the data doesn't show you the full picture. And 
being able to quantify the impact on engagement,  

622
00:59:16,560 --> 00:59:22,240
on profitability, will make it stand out 
as something that really, that you would  

623
00:59:22,240 --> 00:59:27,560
maybe miss if you weren't really looking for it.
And then I think the other thing is with something  

624
00:59:27,560 --> 00:59:33,640
like login errors, sometimes you don't see it 
in the data because people can't even get into  

625
00:59:33,640 --> 00:59:39,880
the data. If you're not able to log in, you're 
not making any purchases, you're not ordering,  

626
00:59:39,880 --> 00:59:44,800
and so you may not see it in the data that you're 
looking at. And so that's also something that I  

627
00:59:44,800 --> 00:59:49,480
think is important for data folks to think about, 
which is what data don't we have? What data might  

628
00:59:49,480 --> 00:59:55,240
we be missing? Where might there be opportunities 
and things that we actually need to identify and  

629
00:59:55,240 --> 01:00:01,120
fix that we may not see? Because in this case, 
with login failures, they're not able to log  

